            "content": "# GridBot — Complete System Flow\n\n## Overview\n\nGridBot is a **grid trading bot** that profits from price oscillations within a defined range. It places a ladder of buy orders below the current price and sell orders above it. When a buy fills, it places a sell one level up; when a sell fills, it places a buy one level down — capturing the spread on each cycle.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Bot Creation & Initialization\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    actor User\n    participant FE as Frontend (React)\n    participant API as Rails API\n    participant DB as PostgreSQL\n    participant SQ as Sidekiq\n    participant Init as Grid::Initializer\n    participant Calc as Grid::Calculator\n    participant EX as Bybit Exchange\n    participant RD as Redis\n\n    User->>FE: Configure bot (pair, range, grid count, investment)\n    FE->>API: POST /api/v1/bots\n    API->>DB: Create Bot (status: pending)\n    API-->>FE: Bot created\n\n    User->>FE: Click \"Start Bot\"\n    FE->>API: PATCH /api/v1/bots/:id {status: running}\n    API->>DB: Bot → initializing\n    API->>SQ: Enqueue BotInitializerJob (critical queue)\n    API-->>FE: 200 OK\n\n    SQ->>Init: Grid::Initializer.call(bot)\n    Init->>EX: GET /v5/market/instruments-info (tick_size, min_qty)\n    Init->>EX: GET /v5/market/tickers (current price)\n    Init->>Calc: Calculate grid levels\n    Calc-->>Init: Array of {price, side} levels\n\n    Note over Calc: Arithmetic: step = (upper-lower)/count<br/>Geometric: ratio = (upper/lower)^(1/count)<br/>Neutral zone: skip levels within 0.1% of current price\n\n    Init->>EX: Market buy (if base asset deficit for sell levels)\n\n    loop For each grid level (except skipped)\n        Init->>EX: POST /v5/order/create (limit order)\n        EX-->>Init: exchange_order_id\n        Init->>DB: Create GridLevel + Order (status: open)\n    end\n\n    Init->>EX: POST /v5/order/disconnected-cancel-all (DCP, 40s window)\n    Init->>RD: Seed bot state (status, levels, stats)\n    Init->>DB: Bot → running\n    Init->>SQ: Schedule GridReconciliationWorker (every 15s)\n```\n\n### Initialization Details\n\n- **Grid calculation**: Levels are spaced either arithmetically (`step = (upper - lower) / count`) or geometrically (`ratio = (upper/lower)^(1/count)`)\n- **Neutral zone**: Levels within 0.1% of the current price are skipped to prevent immediate taker fills\n- **Base asset**: If the bot needs to sell at levels above current price, it first market-buys the required base asset\n- **Order link ID format**: `g{bot_id}-L{level_index}-{B|S}-{cycle_count}` — ensures uniqueness and idempotency\n- **Quantity per level**: `investment_amount / buy_count / current_price`\n- **DCP (Dead Man's Switch)**: Registered with Bybit — if the bot process dies and WebSocket disconnects for >40s, the exchange auto-cancels all orders\n\n---\n\n## 2. Execution Loop — The Core Trading Cycle\n\nThis is where profit is made. Three parallel systems keep the grid alive:\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant WS as WebSocket Listener<br/>(bin/ws_listener)\n    participant EX as Bybit Exchange\n    participant RD as Redis\n    participant SQ as Sidekiq\n    participant FW as OrderFillWorker\n    participant DB as PostgreSQL\n    participant AC as ActionCable\n    participant FE as Frontend\n\n    Note over WS,EX: === A. WebSocket Fill Detection (< 100ms) ===\n\n    WS->>EX: Connect wss://stream.bybit.com/v5/private\n    WS->>EX: Subscribe: order.spot, execution.spot, wallet, tickers\n\n    EX-->>WS: order.spot: orderStatus=Filled (Buy at level N)\n    WS->>RD: Publish to grid:fills stream\n    WS->>SQ: Enqueue OrderFillWorker(order_data)\n\n    Note over FW: === B. Fill Processing (critical queue) ===\n\n    SQ->>FW: Process fill\n    FW->>DB: Find order by exchange_order_id\n    FW->>DB: Lock GridLevel (optimistic locking)\n    FW->>DB: Update order → filled (filled_qty, fee, net_qty)\n\n    alt BUY fill at level N\n        FW->>EX: Place SELL order at level N+1\n        Note over FW: sell_qty = buy_order.net_qty (fee-adjusted)<br/>link_id = g{bot}-L{N+1}-S-{cycle+1}\n        FW->>DB: Create Order (sell, open), update GridLevel\n    else SELL fill at level N\n        FW->>DB: Record Trade (buy_price, sell_price, net_profit)\n        Note over FW: profit = (sell-buy) x qty - fees\n        FW->>EX: Place BUY order at level N-1\n        Note over FW: buy_qty = bot.quantity_per_level<br/>link_id = g{bot}-L{N-1}-B-{cycle+1}\n        FW->>DB: Create Order (buy, open), update GridLevel\n        FW->>DB: Increment grid_level.cycle_count\n    end\n\n    FW->>RD: Update grid:{bot_id}:levels, stats\n    FW->>AC: Broadcast {type: fill, trade, profit}\n    AC-->>FE: Real-time update\n    FE->>FE: Update grid visualization + P&L\n```\n\n### Fill Processing Details\n\n- **Idempotency**: If an order is already `filled`, duplicate WebSocket messages are skipped\n- **Optimistic locking**: GridLevel is locked during processing to prevent race conditions\n- **Net quantity**: When Bybit deducts fees from the received asset (`fee_coin == base_coin && side == buy`), `net_qty = filled_qty - fee` — prevents gradual base asset leakage\n- **Trade recording**: On each completed sell, a Trade record is created linking the buy and sell orders with `net_profit = (sell_price - buy_price) x quantity - total_fees`\n\n---\n\n## 3. Reconciliation — Safety Net\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant RW as ReconciliationWorker<br/>(every 15s)\n    participant EX as Bybit Exchange\n    participant DB as PostgreSQL\n    participant SQ as Sidekiq\n    participant FW as OrderFillWorker\n\n    Note over RW: Triggered every 15s OR on WebSocket disconnect\n\n    RW->>EX: GET /v5/order/realtime (all open orders, paginated)\n    RW->>DB: Load all DB orders with status=open\n\n    Note over RW: Compare exchange state vs DB state\n\n    alt Order in DB but NOT on exchange\n        RW->>EX: GET /v5/order/history (check if filled)\n        alt Was filled (missed by WebSocket)\n            RW->>SQ: Enqueue OrderFillWorker(order_data)\n            SQ->>FW: Process missed fill\n        else Was cancelled/rejected\n            RW->>DB: Mark order cancelled\n        end\n    end\n\n    alt Order on exchange but NOT in DB (orphan)\n        alt Matches bot's link_id pattern\n            RW->>DB: Adopt order (create records)\n        else Foreign order\n            RW->>EX: Cancel orphan order\n        end\n    end\n\n    alt Grid level has no active order (gap)\n        RW->>EX: Place new order at expected price/side\n        RW->>DB: Create Order + update GridLevel\n    end\n```\n\n### Why Both WebSocket and Reconciliation?\n\n| Mechanism | Method | Latency | Reliability |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **WebSocket** | `order.spot` subscription | < 100ms | Not guaranteed (can drop messages) |\n| **Reconciliation** | Poll exchange every 15s | 15s max gap | Guaranteed catch-up |\n\nWebSocket gives near-instant feedback for UX. Reconciliation ensures correctness even if WebSocket drops messages.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Risk Management\n\n```mermaid\nsequenceDiagram\n    participant WS as WebSocket Listener\n    participant EX as Bybit Exchange\n    participant RM as Grid::RiskManager\n    participant DB as PostgreSQL\n    participant RD as Redis\n    participant AC as ActionCable\n    participant FE as Frontend\n\n    EX-->>WS: tickers: price update\n    WS->>RD: Update grid:{bot_id}:current_price\n    WS->>RM: RiskManager.check!(bot, current_price)\n\n    alt Price <= stop_loss_price OR >= take_profit_price\n        RM->>DB: Bot → stopping\n        RM->>EX: POST /v5/order/cancel-all\n        RM->>EX: Market sell all base asset\n        RM->>DB: All orders → cancelled, levels → filled\n        RM->>DB: Bot → stopped (reason: stop_loss | take_profit)\n        RM->>RD: Cleanup bot state\n        RM->>AC: Broadcast {type: status, status: stopped}\n        AC-->>FE: Show stop notification\n    end\n\n    Note over WS,EX: === Trailing Grid (optional) ===\n\n